Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.36,0:00:04.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Welcome to Essential Hayek \N 欢迎来到哈耶克简要
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.72,0:00:06.20,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm Don Boudreaux \N 我是Don Boudreaux
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.20,0:00:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,professor of economics at George Mason University \N 乔治梅森大学经济学教授
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.04,0:00:11.16,Default,,0,0,0,,senior fellow with the Fraser Institute \N 弗雷泽研究所高级研究员
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.16,0:00:13.38,Default,,0,0,0,,and blogger at Café Hayek \N 博客Café Hayek的博主之一
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.38,0:00:16.22,Default,,0,0,0,,This video was part of the Fraser Institute initiative \N 本视频是由弗雷泽研究所制作的
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.22,0:00:21.30,Default,,0,0,0,,to present the key ideas of F.A. Hayek in an easily accessible format \N 对哈耶克关键思想的通俗介绍
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.30,0:00:25.40,Default,,0,0,0,,In this video, we explore one of Hayek's most profound pursuits \N 本视频将介绍哈耶克最重要的思想探索之一
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.40,0:00:30.22,Default,,0,0,0,,which is understanding the difference between legislation and the law \N 立法和法律的不同
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.22,0:00:35.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Hayek differentiated between rules consciously designed and imposed on society by government officials \N 哈耶克区分了两种规则，由政府官员有意设计并施加于社会的、
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.88,0:00:41.74,Default,,0,0,0,,and rules that emerge undesigned from social interaction among people over time \N 和无人设计、在人们的互动中自发涌现的
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.74,0:00:46.12,Default,,0,0,0,,He called rules imposed on society by government officials legislation \N 他把政府制定的社会规范规则称为立法
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.12,0:00:52.28,Default,,0,0,0,,and he contrast legislation with those rules that emerge, which he called law \N 把自发涌现的规则称作法律，并把二者进行了对比
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.28,0:00:57.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Hayek's concept of law is a lot like what we today refer to as social norms \N 哈耶克所说的法律类似于我们今天所说的社会规范
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.68,0:01:01.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's try to simplify this distinction with an example \N 让我们举个栗子来说明这种区分
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.06,0:01:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,This is Julie \N 这是Julie
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.12,0:01:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Julie is going to the movies \N 她正要去看电影
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.56,0:01:07.34,Default,,0,0,0,,When Julie enters the theater \N 当Julie来到电影院
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.34,0:01:10.44,Default,,0,0,0,,she finds a seat and puts a coat on it \N 她找到了个座位并把外套放了上去
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.44,0:01:15.30,Default,,0,0,0,,This small act sends a signal to others that the seat is now taken \N 这个小举动告诉其他人这个位置已经被占了
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.30,0:01:17.66,Default,,0,0,0,,People recognize from the placing of the coat \N 人们会从放在那的外套看出
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.66,0:01:23.12,Default,,0,0,0,,that someone has staked a claim so to speak, on that seat for the duration of the movie \N 已经有人宣示了这个座位在电影放映期间的使用权
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.12,0:01:27.38,Default,,0,0,0,,No one will move Julie's coat or sit in that seat \N 没人会拿开Julie的外套或者去坐那个座位
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.38,0:01:32.42,Default,,0,0,0,,This rule is a social norm or convention that governs our behavior \N 这个规则就是一种约束着我们行为的社会规范，或者叫习俗
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.42,0:01:36.66,Default,,0,0,0,,No government imposed this rule as a law, but so what \N 没有政府把这条规则写进法典，但那又怎样？
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.66,0:01:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,We all recognize and follow this rule \N 我们都理解并遵守这条规则
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.44,0:01:43.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and we would interpret someone who ignores this rule by moving Julie's coat \N 并且假如有人无视这条规则，移走Julie的外套
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.66,0:01:45.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and taking the seat \N 一屁股坐下来
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.66,0:01:49.28,Default,,0,0,0,,as someone who violates the normal social behavior \N 我们会认为他违反了正常的社会规范
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.28,0:01:53.24,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, this social norm constrains the way we act \N 换句话说，这条社会规范限制了我们的行为可能
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.24,0:01:58.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and allows us to interact with one another more effectively \N 并且让我们能更有效地与他人互动
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.02,0:02:02.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Another example can be seen when Julie goes to get popcorn \N 当Julie去买爆米花时，我们可以看到另一个例子
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.90,0:02:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,There is a line at the concession stand \N 人们正在小卖部排队购物
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.34,0:02:10.20,Default,,0,0,0,,but rather than push to the front of line by cutting ahead of everyone \N 不过Julie并没有直接插队到第一个
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.20,0:02:13.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Julie stands at the back and waits for turn \N 而是排在了队伍最后耐心等待
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.86,0:02:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a typical social norm that we all naturally follow without thinking \N 这是一个我们所有人都无需思考就会自然遵守的社会规范
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.18,0:02:20.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and we expect others to do the same \N 并且我们预期别人也会这么做
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.68,0:02:23.88,Default,,0,0,0,,It doesn't require government for its enforcement \N 它也无需政府来保障它的执行
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.88,0:02:27.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Hayek explained how the social norms that emerge over time \N 哈耶克解释了此类
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.50,0:02:31.34,Default,,0,0,0,,through people interacting with one another and figuring out what works \N 通过人们的互动和试错自发产生的社会规范
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.34,0:02:33.96,Default,,0,0,0,,powerfully govern our behaviors toward others \N 是如何有力地约束我们对其他人的行为的
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.96,0:02:40.02,Default,,0,0,0,,so that society functions productively, collaboratively, and peacefully \N 从而让社会和平、有效率、又相互合作
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.02,0:02:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,To learn more and download <Essential Hayek> for free \N 想要下载和更多了解《哈耶克简要》
